<DOC><DOCNO> AP900412-0035 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-90 0305EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-12 0223</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Lites,0234</SECOND><HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD><DATELINE>PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Veteran rabbit raiser Roy Rogers, whowas hopping mad after his rabbitry was raided by thieves, is backin the bunnies.   ``Friends are calling and bringing bunnies every day,'' said the71-year-old Rogers. ``One brought in 19.''   Dozens of would-be Easter bunnies were stolen early Sundaymorning from Roy's Rabbitry in southeastern Mississippi.   The loss suffered by the 71-year-old Rogers attracted nationalattention and scores of calls offering help.   ``I've gotten so many calls,'' Rogers said Wednesday. ``Peoplecall and offer me rabbits saying, `You taught me how to raise them,let me help you now.'''</TEXT><DATELINE>STANLEY, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The town of Stanley cannot make heads ortails of who won its mayoral election.   But instead of flipping a coin to decide it _ as officialsearlier considered _ the city council voted Tuesday night to hold anew election.   In last week's election, the race ended in a tie between twowrite-in candidates, incumbent David Sandberg and challenger FredBeehler. Each had 182 votes.   Lavern Honrud came in third with 103 votes.   Beehler said a coin toss wouldn't be fair to those who voted forHonrud. Sandberg agreed, so the council set the new election forJune 12.   Stanley, in northwestern North Dakota, has a population of about1,000.</TEXT></DOC>